Developments in California's energy crisis=20
The Associated Press
Tuesday, July 24, 2001=20
,2001 Associated Press=20
URL:=20
<http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=3D/news/archive/2001/07/24/=
state
1037EDT0155.DTL>
(07-24) 07:37 PDT (AP) --=20
Developments in California's energy crisis:=20
TUESDAY:
* No power alerts Tuesday as electricity reserves stay above 7 percent.=20
MONDAY:
* U.S. Energy Secretary Spencer Abraham unveils a plan to help alleviate a=
=20
transmission bottleneck that has kept power from flowing freely throughout=
=20
the state during times of peak usage. The plan calls for expanding the=20
state's power grid along so-called Path 15 by attracting private investment=
=20
for the $300 million project.=20
* A Senate committee investigating possible price manipulation has given th=
e=20
full Senate a report asking for Houston-based Enron Corp. to be cited for=
=20
contempt. The Senate Select Committee to Investigate Price Manipulation of=
=20
the Wholesale Energy Market says Enron failed to comply with a subpoena for=
=20
financial and trading documents. The Senate recessed Sunday until Aug. 20 a=
nd=20
could take up the matter when it returns.=20
* Secretary of State Bill Jones asks the state Assembly to allot $250,000 f=
or=20
a legislative review into whether Gov. Gray Davis' advisers complied with=
=20
conflicts of interest laws. Jones, a Republican who plans to challenge Davi=
s=20
in the next election, says the advisers failed to disclose that they held=
=20
stock in energy companies. The Senate rejected a proposal Saturday to earma=
rk=20
that money for a bipartisan investigation. Steve Maviglio, Davis' spokesman=
,=20
says the governor's office, the attorney general and the Fair Political=20
Practices Commission are "working together to resolve any conflicts of=20
interest and to deal appropriately with any violations."=20
* U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Dennis Montali gives Pacific Gas and Electric Co.=
=20
four additional months to produce a reorganization plan in its Chapter 11=
=20
filing. PG&E lawyers had argued for the extension because of the complexity=
=20
of the case. The bankruptcy case is believed to be the largest ever.=20
* The Department of Water Resources says that since July 1, the state has=
=20
sold 177,571 megawatt hours at $36.95 each. During the same time, DWR=20
purchased 3.5 million megawatt hours of electricity at $118 per megawatt=20
hour. That amounts to a loss of about $14 million. Assemblyman John Campbel=
l,=20
R-Irvine, says it's proof the state needs to get out of the power business.=
=20
DWR spokesman Oscar Hildalgo says it's normal for utilities to sell excess=
=20
power they have purchased.=20
* Shares of Edison International close at $13.67, down 57 cents. PG&E Corp.=
=20
stock close at $14.25, down 75 cents. Shares of Sempra Energy, the parent=
=20
company of San Diego Gas & Electric Co., close at $25.20, down $1.09.=20
* No power alerts Monday as electricity reserves stay above 7 percent.=20
WHAT'S NEXT:
* The deadline for the Legislature to approve Davis' rescue deal for Southe=
rn=20
California Edison is Aug. 15.=20
THE PROBLEM:
High demand, high wholesale energy costs, transmission glitches and a tight=
=20
supply worsened by scarce hydroelectric power in the Northwest and=20
maintenance at aging California power plants are all factors in California'=
s=20
electricity crisis.=20
Southern California Edison and Pacific Gas and Electric say they've lost=20
nearly $14 billion since June 2000 to high wholesale prices the state's=20
electricity deregulation law bars them from passing on to consumers. PG&E,=
=20
saying it hasn't received the help it needs from regulators or state=20
lawmakers, filed for federal bankruptcy protection April 6. Electricity and=
=20
natural gas suppliers, scared off by the companies' poor credit ratings, ar=
e=20
refusing to sell to them, leading the state in January to start buying powe=
r=20
for the utilities' nearly 9 million residential and business customers. The=
=20
state is also buying power for a third investor-owned utility, San Diego Ga=
s=20
& Electric, which is in better financial shape than much larger Edison and=
=20
PG&E but is also struggling with high wholesale power costs.=20
The Public Utilities Commission has approved average rate increases of 37=
=20
percent for the heaviest residential customers and 38 percent for commercia=
l=20
customers, and hikes of up to 49 percent for industrial customers and 15=20
percent or 20 percent for agricultural customers to help finance the state'=
s=20
multibillion-dollar power buys.=20








Figures show state lost big on extra power=20
Posted at 9:53 p.m. PDT Monday, July 23, 2001=20
BY JOHN WOOLFOLK=20

Mercury News=20


State figures show California may have lost about $14 million this month=20
selling surplus electricity for less than it cost.=20
The Mercury News disclosed last week that some power was being sold at a=20
loss. But the new figures provide the first indication of just how much=20
excess power the state bought in its desperate effort to avoid blackouts --=
=20
and how cheaply some of that power was sold when it turned out not to be=20
needed.=20
A Republican lawmaker said Monday the loss also shows Democratic Gov. Gray=
=20
Davis' energy policies are needlessly costing consumers.=20
``This whole thing is a mess,'' said Assemblyman John Campbell, R-Irvine, w=
ho=20
requested details of the state's surplus power sales. ``The government need=
s=20
to get out of the power business before it costs Californians even more=20
money.''=20
A state spokesman didn't dispute the $14 million figure outright but said i=
t=20
is an approximation based on average prices and that the actual loss probab=
ly=20
is less.=20
``It's a number I'm sure he likes very much, but it's definitely an estimat=
ed=20
number, and it could be far lower,'' said Oscar Hidalgo, spokesman for the=
=20
state Department of Water Resources.=20
Campbell responded that the loss also could be higher.=20
The state has spent $415 million on power so far this month.=20
State officials last week confirmed that cool weather and consumer=20
conservation have left California holding more power than it needs. The=20
revelation was a stunning turnaround for a state that months ago was paying=
=20
top dollar for power, expecting shortages this summer.=20
Price that was paid=20
The state bought 3.5 million megawatt-hours of electricity for July at an=
=20
average price of $118 per megawatt-hour, according to a response Friday by=
=20
the Department of Water Resources to Campbell's inquiry. The state has sold=
=20
178,000 surplus megawatt-hours in July at an average price of $37, the=20
department said.=20
Based on those average prices, the state paid $21 million for the surplus=
=20
power, which it sold for $6.5 million -- $14.5 million less than it cost.=
=20
A more precise calculation of the state's loss is difficult because purchas=
ed=20
power is acquired at different times and prices and pooled as a=20
``portfolio.''=20
Purchases included long-term contracts that averaged $138 per megawatt-hour=
=20
as well as cheaper spot-market buys.=20
State officials last week said they were selling surplus at $15 to $30 a=20
megawatt-hour, while some traders cited unconfirmed sales as low as $1.=20
Hidalgo noted that the surplus sales represent just 5 percent of California=
's=20
July purchases, which totaled $415 million. The $6.5 million from sales wil=
l=20
help lower the state's power bill, he said, adding that utilities routinely=
=20
sell some extra electricity.=20
``Despite the fact that we're in somewhat of a surplus, any power-buying=20
operation in the world is going to have to plan for these types of=20
situations,'' Hidalgo said. ``It's not unique, and in fact it's normal=20
operating procedure for any utility.''=20
Other Western utilities, including Portland General Electric in Oregon, hav=
e=20
said they, too, are selling some surplus power at a loss and describe it as=
 a=20
cost of doing business.=20
The suppliers buying the state's surplus electricity on the cheap include t=
he=20
big out-of-state energy companies that the governor has called price-gougin=
g=20
``snakes.'' Among them are Duke Energy, Dynegy Power and Marketing, El Paso=
=20
Power Services, Mirant, Reliant Energy and Williams Energy.=20
`Best bid' taken=20
Hidalgo said the state took the best offers it could find.=20
``It's only reasonable to get the best bid you can,'' he said.=20
Campbell said the $14 million loss is troubling because ratepayers or=20
taxpayers will have to cover the cost, whereas a private utility could be=
=20
forced to eat the expense if regulators determined it was unreasonable.=20
State officials say what's more important is that the overall cost of power=
=20
is dropping, from an average daily tab of $64 million in May to $25 million=
=20
this month, in part because the state has so much power.=20


Contact John Woolfolk at jwoolfolk@sjmercury.com=20
<mailto:jwoolfolk@sjmercury.com> or (408) 278-3410.=20







Temperatures likely to rise all week=20
Published Tuesday, July 24, 2001, in the San Jose Mercury News=20
BY DANA HULL=20

Mercury News=20


Temperatures throughout the Bay Area are expected to rise each day this wee=
k,=20
and some inland cities could see low 100s by Thursday or Friday.=20
Despite the warming trend, officials for the California Independent System=
=20
Operator said Monday they should get by without any rolling blackouts. Hott=
er=20
temperatures, often accompanied by spikes in air conditioning use, can stra=
in=20
the state's electric grid.=20
``We believe we'll be fine this week,'' said Lorie O'Donley of the ISO. ``O=
ur=20
understanding of the forecast is some localized heat in Northern=20
California,'' but the coastal regions and Southern California will be more=
=20
moderate.=20
Meteorologists say that the atmospheric ``upper trough,'' or cool air, is=
=20
moving out of the Bay Area.=20
``Cool air has been parked over the West Coast and California,'' said Ryan=
=20
Walbrun, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service. ``It moved in=
=20
shortly after the Fourth of July, but that system is weakening and will mov=
e=20
out. Things will heat up in the Central Valley and eastern portions of the=
=20
Bay Area. It will be a gradual warming trend during the work week.''=20


