(510) 790-7311.=20







Wholesale Competition Contributed to Trend of Lower Power Prices, According=
=20
to New EPSA Study=20

July 24, 2001    <JavaScript:userButton(>  WASHINGTON, July 23 /PRNewswire/=
=20
via NewsEdge Corporation -  Calls for a return to cost-plus rate regulation=
=20
in the wake of the California power crisis are misplaced, according to an=
=20
independent study released today that found that competitive markets=20
contributed to a 36 percent decline in retail electricity prices among=20
surveyed utilities.  "That decrease is in sharp contrast to the increases=
=20
that consumers experienced in the days of solely cost-plus rate regulation,=
"=20
said Electric Power Supply Association President Lynne H. Church, who=20
released the findings during a media luncheon in conjunction with the group=
's=20
summer membership meeting. "This analysis is evidence that we should contin=
ue=20
to move forward toward more competition in order to apply downward pressure=
=20
on prices."  The study: "Assessing the 'Good Old Days' of Cost-Plus=20
Regulation," analyzed sales data for 60 of the nation's investor-owned=20
utilities during 1985-1999, when traditional cost-plus rate regulation bega=
n=20
evolving toward more competition. Complete sales figures for 2000 were not=
=20
yet available when the study was completed. The study was commissioned by=
=20
EPSA and conducted by Craig Roach, Ph.D, principal of Boston Pacific Co.  "=
In=20
the wake of the California power crisis, some people have expressed a longi=
ng=20
for a return to the 'good' old days of cost-plus regulation, but those days=
=20
were far from good," Roach said. "People seem to forget that, in the days o=
f=20
cost-plus regulation between 1970 and 1985, inflation-adjusted electricity=
=20
prices actually increased 25 percent for residential customers and increase=
d=20
86 percent for industrial/commercial customers."  "So much for the good old=
=20
days," Church said. "The price increases under cost-plus regulation were=20
precisely what drove the start of electricity competition in the early and=
=20
mid-1980s."  During the 1985-1999 period, according to the analysis,=20
inflation-adjusted electricity prices decreased an average 30 percent for=
=20
residential customers and 36 percent for industrial/commercial customers. =
=20
"We should not allow the problems in California to cast a false shadow on=
=20
competition," Church said. "The evidence presented in this study makes it=
=20
clear that it would be counterproductive and unwise to go back to the old=
=20
ways."  "It is important to understand that what happened in California=20
resulted, in part, from market rules that prohibited basic risk management,=
"=20
Roach said. "Specifically, utilities were required to take on the risk of=
=20
selling at a fixed price to customers, but not allowed to manage that risk =
by=20
arranging contracts with fixed-price suppliers or use other risk management=
=20
tools. Managing risk appropriately benefits consumers, and risk management =
is=20
more efficient and effective in a truly competitive regime."  "This study=
=20
bolsters our belief that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission should=20
continue to move expeditiously toward more efficient wholesale markets,=20
states should continue to move quickly toward opening their retail power=20
markets, and Congress should quickly adopt comprehensive legislation to hel=
p=20
them along," Church said.  Note: A copy of the complete study is available =
at=20
www.bostonpacific.com/powerprices .  EPSA is the national trade association=
=20
representing independent power producers and power marketers active in U.S.=
=20
and global power markets. As suppliers of reliable, clean, competitively=20
priced electricity, EPSA members seek to bring the benefits of competition =
to=20
all electricity customers.  Contact: Mark Stultz, 202-628-8200  Audrey Duff=
,=20
202-354-8205  MAKE YOUR OPINION COUNT - Click Here =20
http://tbutton.prnewswire.com/prn/11690X71763169  SOURCE Electric Power=20
Supply Association  CONTACT: Mark Stultz of Electric Power Supply=20
Association, +1-202-628-8200; or Audrey Duff, +1-202-354-8205, for Electric=
=20
Power Supply Association  Web site: http://www.epsa.org=20
http://www.bostonpacific.com/powerprices=20
